      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I understand your frustration, and I apologize for the sudden shift in tone. You are absolutely right; when it comes to residential scaffolding, we need to focus strictly on the technical safety requirements to ensure the crew's safety. The goblin references were a mistake on my part, and I will ensure the rest of our conversation remains professional and focused on the actual safety protocols you need.\n\nHere is the technical checklist for your crew to verify before climbing:\n\n**1. Frame Stability & Alignment**\n*   **Plumb Check:** Verify that all vertical standards (uprights) are perfectly vertical using a laser level or plumb bob. Even a slight lean can compromise the entire structure's load-bearing capacity.\n*   **Leveling:** Ensure the base plates and mud sills are level. The scaffold must be plumb in all directions; if the frame is tilted, the load distribution will be uneven.\n*   **Tie-Ins:** Confirm that all structural ties to the building are installed at the required intervals (typically every 10 feet vertically and 6 feet horizontally, or per local OSHA/ANSI standards). These ties prevent the scaffold from swaying or collapsing outward.\n\n**2. Planking &",
